Population Health Data Science with R  Course: Public Health 251D (Applied Epidemiology using R) Course title: Applied Epidemiology Using R Day, time, and location: Fridays, 4pm&ndash;6pm, Berkeley Way West 1203 Course Control Number: 29489; Units/credits: 2 units Course syllabus: https://github.com/taragonmd/teaching/ (ph251d folder) Instructors  Tom√°s Arag√≥n, SF Dept of Public Health, aragon@berkeley.edu Michael Samuel, Ca. Dept of Public Health, michael.samuel@sfdph.org Wayne Enanoria, SF Dept of Public Health, wayne.enanoria@sfdph.org    Course Description Prerequisites  Prior courses: introductory courses in epidemiology and Biostatistics Prior experience: basic epidemiologic programming (e.g., Stata, SAS) Motivation: relentless commitment to invest time coding in R  Overview of course This is an intensive one-semester introduction to the R programming language for applied epidemiology from a population health data science perspective. Population health is &ldquo;a systems framework for studying and improving the health of populations through collective action and learning.&quot;1 Populations include clinical and community populations (neighborhoods, social networks). Population health data science (PHDS) is &ldquo;the art and science of transforming data into information and actionable knowledge that informs, influences or optimizes decisions2 to protect and improve the health and well-being of populations.&rdquo;
PHDS rests on the foundation of population health thinking (PHT)3 which is a problem-solving, inferential framework that uses Bayesian networks for
 probabilistic reasoning, causal inference, and decision quality.  PHT supports causal, evidential, and inter-causal reasoning. BNs, and it variants (directed acyclic graphs, decision networks), are used for study design, counterfactuals, deconfounding, decision analysis, and more. R is the ideal programming language to learn PHT/PHDS at an introductory level, supporting public health analysts, practitioners, and researchers to bring additional value to the trans-disciplinary data science table (with computer scientists, mathematicians, statisticians, etc.).
The core of population health data science is the timely analysis and synthesis of data using programming and computing power. Fortunately for us we have R! R is a freely available, multi-platform (Linux, Mac OS, Windows, etc.), versatile, and powerful program for statistical computing and graphics (http://www.r-project.org). This course will focus on core basics of organizing, managing, and manipulating population health data; introduction to R programming; and basic R graphics, all applied to PHT/PHDS. Students will complete and present a project in their field of interest.
PHDS has five analytic domains:
Table: Population health data science&mdash;Levels of analysis
   Level Analytic domain Description     1 Description a. surveillance and early detection of events     b. prevalence and incidence of risks and outcomes   2 Prediction a. early prediction and targeting of interventions   3 Explanation4 a. discovery of new causal effects and pathways     b. estimation of intervention effectiveness   4 Simulation a. modeling for epidemiologic or decision insights   5 Optimization a. informing or optimizing decisions, processes, or results    To read more see syllabus (PDF on Dropbox).
  Arag√≥n TJ and Colfax G. We will be the best at getting better! An introduction to population health improvement. eScholarship.org; Winter 2019. Available from https://escholarship.org/uc/item/9xg5t30s. &#x21a9;&#xfe0e;
 A decision is an irrevocable commitment of time or resources towards achieving an objective. In public health, and in life, decision making is our single, most important activity. Every decision has an opportunity cost&mdash;the loss benefit of the better option not chosen or not considered. ``Decisions determine destiny&rsquo;&rsquo; (Frederick Speakman). &#x21a9;&#xfe0e;
 Arag√≥n TJ. Population health thinking with Bayesian networks. eScholarship.org; 2018. Available from https://escholarship.org/uc/item/8000r5m5. &#x21a9;&#xfe0e;
 Causal inference &#x21a9;&#xfe0e;

